<subSubSection id="FD507B7311FCF7E8C2252AC2AE204BFB" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="3E62F55A07E4B8168B6BEC2EABA7087D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B1CBD5306132F6EA50422A55F8FEC2E4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Obviously related to 
<taxonomicName id="7A47088206150B57230A806BA3C95A12" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="crinicalyx">
<emphasis id="EF3C51D2E14ED3C5594817A1F4B19452" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea crinicalyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but distinguished by the near absence of peduncles, much longer outer sepals and white or cream flowers. Additionally 
<taxonomicName id="24D5EA1181ECDD48DC7B990AFD40BCAC" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="echinocalyx">
<emphasis id="4EE3B34EB57D3DF46742C1661CBAAD2B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. echinocalyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a much more hirsute plant with fewer flowers in each cyme.
</paragraph>
